   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Adamawa, Borno and Yobe States of North East Nigeria</narrative>
  </recipient-country>
  <sector code="151" percentage="100" vocabulary="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The ongoing humanitarian response has predominantly focused on relatively secure and accessible locations such as Maiduguri and other Local Government Area (LGA) capitals (e.g. Monguno, Bama, Gwoza, Mubi). However, almost 1 million people are believed to reside in inaccessible areas outside these towns, where persistent insecurity makes consistent humanitarian access challenging (HRP 2018). 
Years of conflict have disrupted agricultural activity, market functionality, and supply routes, leading to dire nutrition and food security conditions - an estimated 3.7 million and 3.5 million people to be in need of food and supplementary nutrition assistance, respectively. Borno State faces a particularly challenging food security situation, where 36% of the population are projected to face crisis or emergency phases of food and nutrition security from June-August 2018 (Cadre Harmonise, October 2017).
Displaced, non-displaced and returnee populations also face a deeply difficult protection situation, with the 2018 HRP estimating 5.8 million people in need of assistance. Protection concerns are wide-ranging, including conflict-related violence, gender-based violence, family separation, forced marriage, child marriage, forced displacement, arbitrary detention, seizure of belongings, and abduction. The protection threats facing populations are likely to be most acute in inaccessible rural areas with significant Armed Opposition Group (AOG) presence. A February 2018 REACH assessment focussing on recent displacement into the town of Pulka (Gwoza LGA, Borno State) found that, prior to escaping, civilians had been forcibly held captive in their villages for months by AOGs, who threatened them with beatings or execution if they tried to escape and frequently seized their harvests.</narrative>
  </sector>
